  "title": "Aluminium and Its Compounds",
  "concepts": [
    {
      "title": "Aluminium Oxide",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Compounds of Aluminium</strong></h3><p><strong>1. Aluminium oxide or Alumina, $\\mathbf{A}{{\\mathbf{l}}_{\\mathbf{2}}}{{\\mathbf{O}}_{\\mathbf{3}}}$</strong></p><p>$2\\text{Al}{{(\\text{OH})}_{3}}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{A}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}+3{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}$</p><p>$\\,\\text{A}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}{{\\left( \\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}} \\right)}_{3}}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{A}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}+3\\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}$</p><p>${{\\left( \\text{N}{{\\text{H}}_{4}} \\right)}_{2}}\\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}\\cdot \\text{A}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}{{\\left( \\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}} \\right)}_{3}}\\cdot 24{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{A}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}+2\\text{N}{{\\text{H}}_{3}}+4\\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{3}}+25{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}$</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dcc0c03b9dcaf1afe787"
    },
    {
      "title": "Aluminium Chloride",
      "conceptBody": "<p><strong>2. Aluminium Chloride</strong></p><p>$\\text{AlC}{{\\text{l}}_{3}}$ exists as a dimer, thus attaining an octet of elections.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><p>However, when the halides dissolve in ${{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}$, the high enthalpy of hydration is sufficient to break the covalent dimer into ${{\\left[ \\text{M}{{\\left( {{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O} \\right)}_{6}} \\right]}^{3+}}$ and $3{{\\text{X}}^{-}}$ions.</p><p>$\\text{AlC}{{\\text{l}}_{3}}+3{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}\\xrightarrow{{}}\\text{Al}{{(\\text{OH})}_{3}}+3\\text{HCl}$</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dcc1c03b9dcaf1afe788"
    },
    {
      "title": "Alums",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>&nbsp;Alums</strong></h3><p>Alums have general formula</p><p>${{\\text{M}}_{2}}\\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}\\cdot \\text{M}_{2}^{\\prime }{{\\left( \\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}} \\right)}_{3}}\\cdot 24{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O}$</p><p>where $\\text{M}$ stands for monovalent basic radicals such as $\\text{N}{{\\text{a}}^{+}},{{\\text{K}}^{+}},\\text{R}{{\\text{b}}^{+}},\\text{C}{{\\text{s}}^{+}},\\text{A}{{\\text{g}}^{+}}$etc. and ${{\\text{M}}^{\\prime }}$ for trivalent basic radicals such as $\\text{A}{{\\text{l}}^{3+}},\\text{C}{{\\text{r}}^{3+}},\\text{F}{{\\text{e}}^{3+}},\\text{M}{{\\text{n}}^{3+}},\\text{C}{{\\text{o}}^{3+}}$</p><p>Some examples of alums are:</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} &nbsp;\\text{ Potash Alum } &amp; {{\\text{K}}_{2}}\\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}\\cdot \\text{A}{{\\text{l}}_{2}}{{\\left( \\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}} \\right)}_{3}}\\cdot 24{{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O} \\\\ \\text{ Ferric alum } &amp; {{\\left( \\text{N}{{\\text{H}}_{4}} \\right)}_{2}}\\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}}\\cdot \\text{F}{{\\text{e}}_{2}}{{\\left( \\text{S}{{\\text{O}}_{4}} \\right)}_{3}} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Alums are crystalline compounds. In alums each metal ion is surrounded by six water molecules and the crystals of alums consists of ${{\\left[ \\text{M}{{\\left( {{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O} \\right)}_{6}} \\right]}^{+}},{{\\left[ {{\\text{M}}^{\\prime }}{{\\left( {{\\text{H}}_{2}}\\text{O} \\right)}_{6}} \\right]}^{3+}}$ and $\\text{SO}_{4}^{2-}$ ions.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dcc1c03b9dcaf1afe789"
    }
  ],
